column15: • Has the work area been set out for line and level?
• Has the previous layer passed acceptance criteria?
• Is the correct material being used?
• Is the pavement intended to be Lower Subbase or Upper Subbase?
• Transverse - Offset by not less than 2 m to any underlying pavement layers.
• Place and compact layers so that the surface finish is smooth and uniform.
• Has the material maintained at optimum moisture content (>85%), with additional water being added if required during compaction?
• Area shall withstand test rolling without visible deformation or springing.
• What quantity of soft, wet or unstable material is present?
• Has rectification process been submitted to VicRoads for Review?
• Surface of each compacted layer in good order/condition & free from contamination until the subsequent pavement work is to commence.
• Characteristic Density Ratio % (six tests per lot): Not less than 98.0% Modified (Scale A)
• Test every lot for acceptance until three consecutive lot of like material and/or work have passed the requirements.
• Surface after completion shall be smooth and uniform, free of segmented areas and conforming to grade, thickness and cross-section shown on the drawings.

• All Test reports received and Reviewed as per Requirements for Testing and Acceptance of Surface Level Measurement, Compaction and Post-compaction Gradings and PIs (Clauses 304.06, 304.08, 304.10 and 304.11)
• All Product Non-Conformance(s) recorded and closed (if applicable)

column16: • Is the asphalt mix design considered “General” and does it conform with VicRoads Section 407? Has mix design been approved by CYP D&C JV?
• Has the previous layer passed acceptance criteria?
• For intermediate and base courses surface to be above 5 degrees Celsius. For wearing course installation, surface to be greater then 10 degrees Celsius. Has the above criteria been met?
• Have the existing pits been raised/lowered to meet the surface level of Asphalt?

• The placement of asphalt on the sub-base or granular base for a new pavement or for an overlay of an existing bituminous surfaced pavement shall not commence until approval to proceed is obtained from CYP D&C JV.
• All transverse joints shall be offset from layer to layer by at least 2 m.

• At junctions where the new asphalt mat is required to match the level of existing pavement surface at the limits of work, chases shall be cut into the existing pavement by cold planing as specified in Section 402.

• Asphalt shall be spread in layers at the compacted thicknesses shown on the drawings or specified. Asphalt shall be uniformly compacted Compaction shall not commence until the asphalt has cooled sufficiently to support the rollers without undue displacement.
• The mean surface level and the variation in surface level for the base, intermediate and wearing courses within each lot shall meet the requirements (mean +/- 5mm, standard deviation 8mm)
• Surface finish - Uniform in appearance, free of dragged areas, cracks, open textured patches, and roller marks.

resource: SYM-ITP-005 - Insitu Kerb and Channel (Rev A)

column15: • One lot per days production. To be marked up on lot map.
• Concrete used in kerb extrusion machines shall have a minimum cementitious material content in the finished concrete as follows:
• All works shall be set out in accordance with the drawings and as specified.
• Concrete shall be fed to the machine at a uniform rate. Surfaces shall be free from surface pitting larger than 5 mm diameter.

• Where it is necessary to join to an existing section of profile different from that being constructed, the change of profile shall be made at a constant rate between 10 and 20 mm per metre. Transitions between different profiles shall be made in accordance with the drawings.
• All edgings shall be rendered and have a steel trowel finish. Visible concrete surfaces to have class 3 finish. Hidden surfaces may have a class 4 finish.

• Transverse joints shall be constructed at regular intervals not exceeding 2.5 m. The resultant slot in the edging shall be tooled to a depth of 20 mm to produce a neat groove not less than 5 mm wide on the exposed surfaces.
• Freshly finished exposed concrete surfaces shall be protected from rain or damage from other sources, until hard set has occurred.
• For damaged kerb and channel and edgings, a length of at least 1 m shall be removed and the replacement section shall be:
• Concrete paving including footpaths, edgings, other surfaces and shared use paths shall be shaped to match existing fixtures, e.g. pit covers, edgings and vehicle crossings, within 5 mm.
• All Product Non-Conformance(s) recorded and closed (if applicable)
• Concrete mix design approved by the Superintendent and a registered mix and Material properties meet project specifications
• Are the drawings, complete & current?Attach Recent IFC Drawings
• Is the work area clearly pegged out for line and level?
• Is edging constructed over Pavement layer?
• Where edgings are constructed over pavement layers, bedding shall be provided between the pavement layer and the underside of the edging, or the edging thickened to match the pavement layer.
• Is bedding for footpaths and surfaces compacted to 100mm thickness unless noted otherwise.
• Is bedding for SUPs, bedding compacted to 150mm thick unless noted otherwise.
• Bedding shall be moist but shall have no free water on the surface before concrete is placed

• Is bedding material used for cast in place concrete paving works compacted size 20 mm Class 3 or Class 4 crushed rock or Class 3 or Class 4 crushed concrete, manufactured and supplied in accordance with Sections 812 or 820 respectively.
• Is bedding material for shared use paths compacted size 20 mm Class 3 crushed rock or Class 3 crushed concrete in accordance with Section 812 or 820 respectively, and Section 304.
• Are pavement lots tested for compliance with the specified compaction scale for moisture content no less than 85%
• Is fill material used below bedding tested to Table Compaction Requirements

resource: SYM-ITP-005 - Insitu Kerb and Channel (Rev A)

column15: • One lot per days production. To be marked up on lot map.
• Concrete used in kerb extrusion machines shall have a minimum cementitious material content in the finished concrete as follows:
• All works shall be set out in accordance with the drawings and as specified.
• Concrete shall be fed to the machine at a uniform rate. Surfaces shall be free from surface pitting larger than 5 mm diameter.

• Where it is necessary to join to an existing section of profile different from that being constructed, the change of profile shall be made at a constant rate between 10 and 20 mm per metre. Transitions between different profiles shall be made in accordance with the drawings.
• All edgings shall be rendered and have a steel trowel finish. Visible concrete surfaces to have class 3 finish. Hidden surfaces may have a class 4 finish.

• Transverse joints shall be constructed at regular intervals not exceeding 2.5 m. The resultant slot in the edging shall be tooled to a depth of 20 mm to produce a neat groove not less than 5 mm wide on the exposed surfaces.
• Freshly finished exposed concrete surfaces shall be protected from rain or damage from other sources, until hard set has occurred.
• For damaged kerb and channel and edgings, a length of at least 1 m shall be removed and the replacement section shall be:
• Concrete paving including footpaths, edgings, other surfaces and shared use paths shall be shaped to match existing fixtures, e.g. pit covers, edgings and vehicle crossings, within 5 mm.
• All Product Non-Conformance(s) recorded and closed (if applicable)
